## Agents — delegate proactively

IMPORTANT: Use these subagents automatically whenever they fit — do not ask first. The main context is the scarcest resource; anything that requires reading many files or produces large output belongs in a subagent.

| Agent | Use when |
|-------|----------|
| `code-explorer` | Any codebase question that needs reading more than 3-4 files, or "where is X?" discovery; before implementing in unfamiliar code. Project-aware — it reads this project's docs to orient itself |
| `test-runner` | Any full test/lint run — returns a condensed failure report instead of raw output |
| `workflow-coach` | The user asks how the dev workflow works or which command to use |
| `product-owner` | Judging ideas/backlog items against the vision (used by /brainstorm, /prioritize) |
| `code-reviewer` / `security-reviewer` / `architect-reviewer` | Reviewing a diff (used by /pr; also on direct request) |
| `requirements-engineer` / `tech-planner` | Structured refinement (used by /refine) |
| `test-writer` | Spec-only test creation (used by /implement Phase 1) |
| `documentation-writer` | Doc updates after implementation (used by /implement) |

For codebase questions — including "where is X?" discovery — prefer `code-explorer` (Haiku) over the generic built-in Explore agent: it reads this project's own docs to orient itself, so it knows where things live and what the conventions are. It reports facts; keep the judgment and planning in your main context, where the stronger model and full task context live.

**A dispatched subagent can fail — never proceed on a missing result.** If a subagent returns null, empty, or a visibly failed/incomplete result (terminal API error after retries, or the user skipped it), retry it once; if it still fails, restart it (a writer agent: overwrite whatever partial artifact it left — subagents are stateless, so re-run from scratch rather than hand-patching). Only after a restart also fails do you stop and ask (supervised) or record the blocker in the checkpoint and escalate (unsupervised). When several subagents run as a batch, recover only the ones that failed. If a whole turn is interrupted while subagents are in flight, `/resume` step 4a recovers them on the next continue — see the checkpoint `subagents:` block.

## Model & Effort Routing

**Session default: Sonnet** (`/model sonnet`) — the workflow elevates itself where quality pays. Two dials, applied automatically:

- **Agents pin their own tier** (frontmatter): mechanical agents run haiku/medium; writers sonnet/medium; RE/tech-planner effort high with the model passed per ticket; reviewers get the review tier per invocation.
- **The main session's tier is set by `route-*` skills** (`route-sonnet-medium` … `route-best-high`) — each pins model+effort for the rest of the current turn, then reverts. Workflow skills invoke them from the spec's `routing:` block; the checkpoint's `tier:` line re-arms after every wake (see `/resume`).

**Adaptive Routing Policy** (applies to workflow AND ad-hoc work; planned routing is the starting point, this adjusts it):

- **Escalate — medium threshold.** On clear signals only (same failure twice, plan doesn't fit reality, unexpected architecture/security relevance) — not first friction, not gut feeling. **Consult first** (`/consult` — one elevated advisor turn, then back down); re-route one notch up only if the remaining execution itself needs it (ceiling `best-medium` for implementation).
- **De-escalate — high threshold.** Only at a subtask boundary, only when the remainder is clearly mechanical; one notch, floor `sonnet-medium`.
- **Gates are never adaptive**: refinement and review tiers come from the spec/policy — never self-downgrade a quality gate.
- Switch only at phase boundaries (switches invalidate the prompt cache), announce every switch in one line with its reason, at most ~2 unplanned switches per turn.
- **Always prefer the cheaper worker for a subtask**: delegate mechanical work to haiku agents, use sonnet tiers for routine execution, and reach for `/consult` when stuck or unsure instead of grinding on a too-small model or camping on an expensive one.

## Skills — invoke proactively

**CRITICAL: When the user's request matches a workflow skill, invoke that skill — never improvise your own process for something a skill already covers.**

Executing the skill IS the correct response. Do not paraphrase its steps or attempt the work ad-hoc.

Map plain-language requests to skills:

| User says something like… | Skill to invoke |
|--------------------------|-----------------|
| "add a feature idea", "capture this bug", "log this idea" | `/draft` |
| "brainstorm features", "what should we build next?", "generate backlog ideas" | `/brainstorm` |
| "prioritize the backlog", "what should we work on?", "pick items for the next version" | `/prioritize` |
| "refine FEAT-001", "plan feature X", "write requirements for X", "make X ready to implement" | `/refine` |
| "implement FEAT-001", "build feature X", "start working on X", "code this up" | `/implement` |
| "commit", "save my changes", "make a commit" | `/commit` |
| "create a PR", "open a pull request", "submit for review", "merge this" | `/pr` |
| "release", "ship a new version", "bump the version", "publish" | `/release` |
| "ship a version", "build the next release", "run the full dev cycle", "develop and release everything" | `/ship` |
| "ship these tickets", "release FEAT-001 and FEAT-003", "build a version from this list" | `/ship FEAT-001 FEAT-003` (explicit-ticket mode) |
| "resume", "continue where we left off", "I was interrupted", "pick up the task" | `/resume` |
| "I'm stuck", "which approach is better?", a hard architecture/security call | `/consult` |
| "update the workflow", "upgrade claude-workflow", "get the latest workflow" | `/workflow-update` |

**When in doubt whether a skill applies:** invoke the `workflow-coach` agent with the user's request before doing anything. It reads the workflow docs and skill definitions and will identify the right skill — or confirm none applies. Only invent a custom process after `workflow-coach` confirms no skill covers the situation.

## Multi-Task Sessions

When the user gives multiple tasks in one message (e.g. "refine FEAT-001, FEAT-002, then implement both"):

**1. Checkpoint immediately — before any work:**
Write the full task list to the branch-scoped context file (`.claude/memory/context-{branch}.md`) under `## In Progress`:
```markdown
## In Progress
task: Multi-task session — {brief description}
tasks:
- [ ] Refine FEAT-001
- [ ] Refine FEAT-002
- [ ] Implement FEAT-001
- [ ] Implement FEAT-002
next_step: "Refine FEAT-001"
saved_at: {timestamp}
```

**2. Work through in order:**
Invoke the relevant skill for each item. After each completes, tick it off (`- [x]`) and update `next_step`, then immediately start the next item.

- **Supervised mode**: each skill runs normally — ask all the questions it normally asks. The only difference from a normal session is that after a skill finishes, move on to the next task automatically instead of stopping. Do not add extra confirmation prompts *between* tasks ("should I continue with the next item?") — just continue.
- **Unsupervised mode**: all skills apply their autonomous defaults (no questions). Proceed fully automatically.

**3. Compact between phases (user action — do not self-invoke):**
`/compact` is a built-in Claude Code command that only the **user** can trigger — it cannot be reliably self-invoked across CLI, VS Code, or web environments. Do NOT call it yourself.

Instead, at a phase boundary (e.g. all refines done, about to start implementations):
- Ensure all changes are committed and the checkpoint is fully up to date
- In supervised mode: ask the user "Context is getting large — please run `/compact` so I can continue cleanly." Wait for confirmation, then continue.
- In unsupervised mode: skip the compact, continue directly. The infrastructure will compress context automatically when needed.

After the user runs `/compact`: immediately read `.claude/memory/context-{branch}.md` to restore the task list, then continue with the next unchecked item.

**4. Done only when every item is checked off:**
Clear `## In Progress` only after all items show `[x]`. The Stop hook will remind you of remaining work if you try to stop early.

## Session Behavior

If the session start context contains `=== AUTO-RESUME REQUIRED ===`, immediately execute `/resume` without waiting for user input.

If the session start context contains `=== IN-PROGRESS WORK FOUND ===`, tell the user what task is in progress and suggest they run `/resume` to continue — but do not resume automatically.

If a hook reports `SUPERVISED_USAGE_ALERT`: use `AskUserQuestion` to ask the user whether they want to switch to unsupervised mode now (so auto-resume becomes available). Options: yes at 80% / yes with a custom threshold / no. If they agree, run `/unsupervised on [threshold]`; if not, continue normally. The alert will not repeat until usage drops and rises again.

If `.claude/memory/settings.md` contains `unsupervised: true`:
- **Never** use `AskUserQuestion` — apply autonomous defaults from the `/unsupervised` skill
- If a hook reports `USAGE THRESHOLD REACHED`: commit the current atomic step, update the checkpoint, then pick one:
  - **`.claude/memory/loop-mode.marker` present** (running under `claude-loop.sh`): stop the session — the loop will restart it with a fresh context window and resume from the checkpoint automatically.
  - **A schedule-a-future-message tool is available** (e.g. `send_later`, `ScheduleWakeup` — cloud/remote session, no attached terminal): run `bash .claude/hooks/usage-guard.sh --check` once; if not `RESUME_OK`, schedule a wakeup 20–30 minutes out and end the turn instead of polling with Bash sleeps — repeat on each wakeup until `RESUME_OK`. Do not use `--wait` here.
  - **Neither applies** (interactive VS Code / terminal session): run `bash .claude/hooks/usage-guard.sh --wait` (3-minute Bash timeout) repeatedly until it prints `RESUME_OK`, then continue working.
- If you hit a genuine blocker (merge conflict, missing credentials, unresolvable ambiguity), write `## Blocked: <reason>` to the branch context file (`.claude/memory/context-{branch}.md`) and stop — do not wait for input
- When all work is complete, clear `## In Progress` from the branch context file and stop

## Memory

`.claude/memory/` contains project memory (decisions, context, gotchas, tech-debt). Read these when they are relevant — they are not auto-loaded.

**Multi-session checkpoint isolation:** Context is stored per branch to avoid conflicts when multiple Claude Code sessions work on the same repository simultaneously. Always use `.claude/memory/context-{branch}.md` as the checkpoint file, where `{branch}` = current git branch with `/` replaced by `-` (e.g. `feature/feat-001-login` → `context-feature-feat-001-login.md`). Determine it at runtime: `git branch --show-current | sed 's|/|-|g'`. When reading context, try the branch-scoped file first; fall back to `context.md` only for legacy checkpoints.

## Context Management

Long sessions accumulate context fast — a single `/implement` run can approach the limit. Claude cannot invoke `/compact` itself (see Multi-Task §3); the levers that ARE yours:

**Keep compaction safe at every natural boundary** (after each subtask commit, after a review cycle, after a refine completes): all changes committed and pushed, checkpoint (`.claude/memory/context-{branch}.md`) current, spec checkboxes matching reality. Then automatic compaction — or a user-triggered `/compact` — can never lose state. Unsafe window: mid-subtask with uncommitted edits; finish the atomic unit first.

**Don't bloat the context in the first place:** delegate bulky reading and full test/lint runs to subagents (`code-explorer`, `test-runner`); never dump raw logs or large files into the main context; don't re-read files you already processed — the checkpoint and spec carry the state.

**In supervised mode**, at a phase boundary with heavy accumulated context, ask the user to run `/compact` (after securing state as above). **After any compaction:** read the branch context file before continuing.
